[2026-04-04 15:45:23.441] [PRINT]     "content": "What specific key points from the Day 1, 2, and 3 conference talks were most striking to you? Give one concrete learning for each conference talk.\nThe first day's discussion on vocation led to the realization that studying is a sacred obligation to find truth and develop holiness, not just to pass exams. Inspired by St. Thomas Aquinas, I learned that seeking truth requires courage, even if it means sacrificing comfort or opposing corruption. The second day broadened my understanding of love, defining it as the purposeful pursuit of the other person's unconditional well-being, persevering through changing emotions and trials. Finally, the third day's mission reflection emphasized that hope is absorbed through inspiration and companionship, caught by believing in a person's greatest qualities through shared experiences.\n\nHow did the university retreat help you personally? What aspects of your life you felt the retreat became most helpful?\nThe university retreat helped me confront the pessimism that had inadvertently seeped into my heart regarding love and relationships. I realized my tendency to anticipate failure or shield myself from disappointment was a form of despair, impeding necessary personal development. The retreat also reframed my academic life, helping me view my education as a vocation intertwined with spiritual development, rather than a mere duty. This gave me clarity: my goal as a Thomasian student is to seek truth with integrity and let knowledge guide me toward holiness.\n\nAfter attending the ALAB 2026 UST retreat, what concrete personal actions will you undertake to respond to the call of the retreat of \u201cmissionary rekindling\u201d as a Thomasian student? How do you bear witness to the retreat\u2019s theme, \u201cALAB 2026: Pananampalataya, Pag-asa, Pag-ibig?\nI will integrate prayer into my studies, viewing my academic work as a holy pursuit of truth and holiness, thereby answering the missionary call. I will practice the pedagogy of hope by being truly present with classmates, believing in their potential so that hope is caught, not just taught. I will intentionally choose to will the good of others, even when feelings fade, allowing love to be refined and endure through challenges, instead of retreating into cynicism. By trusting God's timing over my own wishes, I will avoid arrogance and despair. I will embody the ALAB 2026 theme letting the fires of truth, love, and hope transform my life by living faith through my studies, hope through companionship, and love through thoughtful choices.\n\n",
[2026-04-04 15:45:23.441] [PRINT]     "title": ""
[2026-04-04 15:45:23.441] [PRINT]   },
[2026-04-04 15:45:23.441] [PRINT]   "raw_response": "Document content:\n\nWhat specific key points from the Day 1, 2, and 3 conference talks were most striking to you? Give one concrete learning for each conference talk.\nThe first day's discussion on vocation led to the realization that studying is a sacred obligation to find truth and develop holiness, not just to pass exams. Inspired by St. Thomas Aquinas, I learned that seeking truth requires courage, even if it means sacrificing comfort or opposing corruption. The second day broadened my understanding of love, defining it as the purposeful pursuit of the other person's unconditional well-being, persevering through changing emotions and trials. Finally, the third day's mission reflection emphasized that hope is absorbed through inspiration and companionship, caught by believing in a person's greatest qualities through shared experiences.\n\nHow did the university retreat help you personally? What aspects of your life you felt the retreat became most helpful?\nThe university retreat helped me confront the pessimism that had inadvertently seeped into my heart regarding love and relationships. I realized my tendency to anticipate failure or shield myself from disappointment was a form of despair, impeding necessary personal development. The retreat also reframed my academic life, helping me view my education as a vocation intertwined with spiritual development, rather than a mere duty. This gave me clarity: my goal as a Thomasian student is to seek truth with integrity and let knowledge guide me toward holiness.\n\nAfter attending the ALAB 2026 UST retreat, what concrete personal actions will you undertake to respond to the call of the retreat of \u201cmissionary rekindling\u201d as a Thomasian student? How do you bear witness to the retreat\u2019s theme, \u201cALAB 2026: Pananampalataya, Pag-asa, Pag-ibig?\nI will integrate prayer into my studies, viewing my academic work as a holy pursuit of truth and holiness, thereby answering the missionary call. I will practice the pedagogy of hope by being truly present with classmates, believing in their potential so that hope is caught, not just taught. I will intentionally choose to will the good of others, even when feelings fade, allowing love to be refined and endure through challenges, instead of retreating into cynicism. By trusting God's timing over my own wishes, I will avoid arrogance and despair. I will embody the ALAB 2026 theme letting the fires of truth, love, and hope transform my life by living faith through my studies, hope through companionship, and love through thoughtful choices.\n\n\n\nDocument ID: 1A_b4e2BSTcdPv7IRxo0b9QtEoa28Jya6ryI-3VF2jsw\nURL: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1A_b4e2BSTcdPv7IRxo0b9QtEoa28Jya6ryI-3VF2jsw/edit",
[2026-04-04 15:45:23.441] [PRINT]   "error": null
[2026-04-04 15:45:23.441] [PRINT] }
